<p align="center">
<b>
<font color="#000080" size="5">Session 4: Acceleration 1 (constant acceleration)</font>
</b>
</p>
</h2>




<p>
<font color="#008000" size="4">Construct an object to move horizontally and add the equation:

<font size="4"> 
<font color="#000000"> <b> 
<p type="equation" version="2.0.0" replaceAppearance="equation" equationMathML="<apply><eq/><apply><mo>Ax</mo><ci>ME</ci><ci>t</ci></apply><cn>2</cn></apply>">
Ax(ME, t) = 2 
</p></b></font>
</font>
</p>


<p>
<font color="#008000" size="4">
<ul>
<li>Change the 2 in this last equation to different values. Play the model each time and notice what happens.
</li>
<li>Try using negative numbers. What do you notice? Why does this happen?</li>
</ul>
</font>
</p>

<div style='border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;'>

<p>
<font color="#008000" size="4"> 
<b><i>'Just as the 
velocity tells you how the position of a particle changes with time, the acceleration tells you how 
the velocity changes with time' </i></b>(M1, p. 29)
</font>
</p>

</div>

<font color="#008000" size="4">
<ul>
<li>Now make an object that accelerates in a vertical direction
</li>
<li>Make an object that first moves upwards and then moves down. 
</li>
<li>Save this model.
</li>
</ul>
</font></p>

<p>
<font color="#008000" size="4"> 
<i>Notice that the equation </i>
</font>
</p>
<font size="4">
<font color="#000000"> <b> 
<p type="equation" version="2.0.0" replaceAppearance="equation" equationMathML="<apply><eq/><apply><mo>Ay</mo><ci>ME</ci><ci>t</ci></apply><ci>-.098</ci></apply>">

Ay(ME,t)=-0.98 
</p></b></font>
</font>


<p>
<font color="#008000" size="4"><i>for acceleration in the vertical direction has an effect 
similar to that of gravity (gravity = - 9.8 m/sec2).</i>

</font>

</p>

